Otherwise, graphene quantum dots (Gr-QDs) with their remarkable features such as high charge carriers’ mobility, large surface area, stability, echo-friendship, multiple exciton photogeneration, and adjustable engineered energy gap that follows the quantum confinement phenomena have supported the nanodevices' efficient performances and substantially manipulated the thermalization deficiency of conventional solar cells that deteriorates PCE 
                     [40–42]. The cell's thermalization deterioration has been resolved by the engineered energy gap of Gr-QDs which provides the proper high energetic photons (E > 2Eg
                     ) absorption and yields net separated e-h pairs rather than that resulting in hot charge carriers and thermal energy in conventional forms of semiconductors [43]. Successfully, Gr-QDs/Si heterojunction cells have been fabricated and achieved PCE of about 6.63 % [44], while embedding graphene quantum rings (Gr-QRs) to PEDOT:PSS in organic/inorganic cell enhanced the PCE from 5.102 % to 7.4 % [45]. Besides, it should be considered the role of QDs in controlling the conduction mechanism of the charge carriers, especially in providing a trap-free system suppressing the dark current that arises from the random generation of e-h pairs within the depletion region [46,47]

The characteristic current density-voltage (J-V) and power-voltage (P-V) curves of the designed devices as solar cells under 100 mW/cm2 are plotted as shown in Fig. 13
                        (a) and (b), respectively. Undoubtedly, the insertion of PEDOT:PSS between the rGO-QDs and silicon induced a significant modification of the solar cell performance in terms of open circuit voltage (Voc
                        ), short circuit current density (Jsc
                        ), and maximum power (Pmax
                        ). The insertion of PEDOT:PSS limited the high dark current induced by the rGO-QDs and manipulated the interfacial contact surface of the junction reducing the density of the interfacial trapping states which hold the e-h to be recombined. Furthermore, the good conductivity of the utilized PEDOT:PSS facilitated the charge carriers’ transportation by providing additional pathways for hole transport owing to its high mobility hindering the recombination process at the interface of the junction. Keeping in mind the vital role of PEDOT:PSS absorption in photogeneration of a higher density of e-h pairs under illumination [45].

As illustrated in Fig. 17(g), the SNR increases significantly as the reverse bias voltage increases and PD-D2 achieves higher SNR than PD-D1. Furthermore, to ensure the speed of the processing and the transmission of electrical signals between the components of the detection circuit and the sensor, it is preferable that the photodetector be linear in its behavior so that we can use it in applications. LDR = 20 log (Jphoto
                        /Jdark
                        ) is the formula for the linear dynamic range (LDR), also known as the photosensitivity linearity. It is observed that PD-D1 exhibits lower linearity (22.5 dB) than PD-D2 (40 dB) as shown in Fig. 17(h), and each increases with increasing the bias voltage. The recorded LDR is close to that recorded for PEDOT:PSS/ SiNWs PDs [95], but lower than those of Si, InGaAs, and other GQDs-based PDs [83]. As it is well known, most photodetectors based on graphene or graphene oxide suffer limited linear dynamic range because of the photothermoelectric effect (PTE) [96].

The dynamical photoresponse of the designed PDs for choppered laser light signals with repeatable on/off switching cycles have been investigated under the influence of different bias voltages as shown in Fig. 18
                        (a) and (b). Both PDs achieved fast reproducible photocurrent response signals, but the stability of the photocurrent of PD-D2 is much higher than that of PD-D1. Interestingly, PD-D2 exhibits spike-like form on/off switching, where under illumination the photocurrent suddenly fast increases and is followed by slow decay and saturation at a definite value of photocurrent. Then decays after switching the illimitation off. The slow decay of photocurrent under illumination on state may be due to capturing the ultrashort lifetime photon-induced charges by traps [97]. Additionally, the pyro-phototronic effect may be responsible for this spike since the thermal-induced charges by the pyroelectric effect cause a sudden increase in the net current, which may be captured rapidly owing to its short lifetime [98]. The decay time of the spike current (td
                        ) of PD-D2 has been increased from 238 ms to 1216 ms upon increasing the applied reverse voltage. Meanwhile, the estimated rise time (tr
                        ) and fall time (tf
                        ) of PD-D1 changed from 30 ms to 23 ms and from 70 ms to 22.4 ms, respectively, upon increasing the reverse bias voltage from -1 volt to -5 volt, while the on/off ratio is slightly increased from 1.15 to 3.47. On the other side, the rise time has been decreased from 30 ms to 15.2 ms and the fall time decreased from 35.2 ms to 19 ms upon increasing reverse bias voltage from -1 volt to −5 Vs, while the on/off ratio is slightly enhanced from 1.69 to 17.57. The decrement of both tr
                         and tf
                         for both devices as the reverse bias voltage increases is a logical observation owing to increasing the drift velocity of charge carriers since the transient response comprises three dynamical processes sweeping the photo-induced carriers by built-in potential, diffusion of out-depletion region charges and diffusion of deep-generated charges. The deep-generated charges may suffer a high probability of recombination during their flight toward the depletion region [83,89,94,97]. Also, the increment of bias voltage enhances the detrapping process of the generated charges which enhances the on/off ratio of each device [83,99].
